Show HN: Fio: 3D World editor/game engine ¢ inspired by Radiant and Hammer | Hacker News
https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=47535626
============================================================

SUMMARY
-------
Fio is a newly released, lightweight 3D world editor and game engine inspired by classic brush-based tools like Radiant and Worldcraft/Hammer. It utilizes a Constructive Solid Geometry (CSG) workflow, features a unified forward renderer with real-time stencil shadows, and is designed to run on modest hardware like the Snapdragon 8CX using OpenGL 3.3.

KEY THEMES
----------
  Ģ Nostalgia for 90s/2000s level design workflows (Quake/Source eras)
  Ģ Game engine market saturation and the difficulty of gaining visibility
  Ģ Technical implementation of classic rendering and optimization techniques (CSG, BSPs, stencil shadows)
  Ģ The transition from hobbyist level design to professional software development

NOTABLE INSIGHTS
----------------
  1. The engine avoids pre-baked lightmaps, opting for real-time lighting with stencil shadows, which is a departure from the traditional workflows of the tools it was inspired by.
  2. Veteran developers in the space suggest that a new engine requires a Unique Selling Proposition (USP) and significant marketing/SEO effort to survive in a saturated market.
  3. The project currently includes 14 examples but is seeking community contributions for features like angled brushes and new entity types.
  4. Targeting specific, lower-power hardware like the Snapdragon 8CX suggests a focus on portability and efficiency over high-end graphical features.

COMMUNITY SENTIMENT
-------------------
The sentiment is a mix of warm nostalgia and professional realism. While users are excited by the 'old school' workflow, there is a clear warning about the competitive landscape of modern game engines.

CONTROVERSY SIGNAL
------------------
Low. The discussion is constructive, though there is a slight tension between the technical enthusiasm for a new tool and the pragmatic skepticism regarding its market viability.

REASONING TRACE
---------------
I reviewed the submission text and the six comments provided. I categorized the responses into nostalgic appreciation (voidfunc, HauntingPin), technical inquiry (LarsDu88, tines), and industry-level critique (samiv). I synthesized the technical specifications from the OP's description to provide a technical summary, then mapped the community's primary concerns and interests to the themes and insights sections.

